    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Yeah, that part about \"unlimited liability\" is what's really stressing me out. It feels like there are all these hidden risks buried in the wording that I might not see until it's too late. Are there any specific words or phrases in a clause like that that usually signal these kinds of \"trap\" liabilities? Like, what should I be looking for to spot anything sneaky?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, there are several specific \"danger words\" that act like a warning siren for hidden liabilities, and spotting them is crucial for a freelancer to avoid getting trapped.\n\nFirst, look for the phrase **\"any and all,\"** which is the biggest red flag because it removes any logical limits on what you are responsible for. It means even a tiny, unrelated mistake could trigger the indemnity.\n\nSecond, watch out for **\"arising out of or occurring in connection with.\"** This is a very broad catch-all phrase that creates a \"net\" wide enough to catch almost any claim, even if the lawsuit is based on something completely unrelated to your work.\n\nThird, be wary of **\"defenses, costs, or expenses of whatever kind.\"** This ensures that even if you win the lawsuit, you might still have to pay the other side's legal fees, which can be astronomical.\n\nFinally, if the clause doesn't explicitly mention a **dollar cap** or a **limitation of liability**, you are effectively agreeing to unlimited financial risk.\n\nTo protect yourself, you should try to replace these broad phrases with more specific ones that limit your liability to your gross profit or a fixed amount.\n\nIf you don't negotiate",
      "source": "target",
